{"id":"1511.01800","submitter":"Raissa M. D'Souza","authors":"Raissa M. D'Souza and Jan Nagler","title":"Explosive Percolation: Novel critical and supercritical phenomena","comments":"Early version of \"Anomalous critical and supercritical phenomena in\n  explosive percolation\" Nature Physics, 11(7), 531, 2015. The final version\n  will be updated here in January 2016. . Cover article","journal-ref":"Nature Physics, 11(7), 531-538, 2015","doi":"10.1038/nphys3378","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Explosive Percolation describes the abrupt onset of large-scale connectivity\nthat results from a simple random process designed to delay the onset of the\ntransition on an underlying random network or lattice. Explosive percolation\ntransitions exhibit an array of novel universality classes and supercritical\nbehaviors including a stochastic sequence of discontinuous transitions,\nmultiple giant components, and lack of self-averaging. Many mechanisms that\ngive rise to explosive percolation have been discovered, including overtaking,\ncorrelated percolation, and evolution on hierarchical lattices. Many\nconnections to real-world systems, ranging from social networks to nanotubes,\nhave been identified and explosive percolation is an emerging paradigm for\nmodeling these systems as well as the consequences of small interventions\nintended to delay phase transitions. This review aims to synthesize existing\nresults on explosive percolation and to identify fruitful directions for future\nresearch.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 Nov 2015 16:22:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-11-06"}
